This line is required for cases where "resp" is empty, which in this case debatably can't happen, but we try to be consistent about it because it has lead to bugs in the past.

FWIW, in new code, I think the ideally pattern we would follow is something like

nlohmann::json::array_t members;

for (a : resp){
   foo.emplace_back(...);
}
asyncResp->res.jsonValue["Members"] = std::move(members);



We don't follow that pattern very often, but I find it the most "obviously correct" version of how to write that code.

nit, i'm trying to get rid of brace initialization of nlohmann objects.

this should be

nlohmann::json::ojbect_t reference;
reference["odata.id"] = urlFromPieces("redfish", "v1", "Chassis", chassisId, "Drives");
asyncResp->res.jsonValue["Drives"] = std::move(reference);



FWIW, I need to write a helper function for navigation references, but that is yet to be done.

I'm almost certain this isn't what you intended to write.  This:

1. Creates a new object in the root of the response (not in members)
2. places the url into the root object (overriding @odata.id)
3. then pushes a COPY of this root object onto members.



I'm pretty sure you meant:

nlohmann::json::object_t member;
member["@odata.id"] = crow::utility::urlFromPieces(...);
members.push_back(std::move(member));



I would've expected this to fail the validator, but oh well, probably did weird stuff in a way that didn't fail.
